description: All available Chrome urls, up to date.
This command shows the accessibility information for each Chrome tab. Here, you are also given the option to turn it ON or OFF.
Appache-internals tells you about the app-cached websites and the storage space used by them.
It shows you all the applications installed in Chrome web browser.
This command shows you the information about blobs (Binary Large Objects).
It shows your web browser’s bookmarks and options to manage them. No points for guessing, obviously.
Cache command is used to list all the cached items like images, website data, and scripts.
It opens the About page of your Google Chrome web browser that tells the current version and the available updates.
This URL displays the complete list of Chrome URLs.
Components command loads a list of all Chrome components like CRLset, recovery, pnacl etc.. Here, you have the option to check for individual updates.
It shows information regarding Google Copresence which allows your web browser to talk to nearby devices.
Here, you can see details of all the recent crashes.
It’s a long list of technologies included in Chrome and their creators.
Device log shows a log of different device related events.
It presents a list of different physical or virtual devices connected to Chrome. You also have the option to manage Google Cloud Print.
Just in case prefetching is enabled in your web browser, this command loads the prefetched DNS records.
All your downloads are listed here.
This page lets you manage all the extensions installed in your web browser.
Flags is the most interesting Chrome URL. Here, you can access different experimental features.
You can find information about Flash plugin and Chrome-Flash integration.
This page displays information about Google Cloud Messaging.
Here, you get to know about your video card and graphics feature status.
Just in case you need support or more information, it opens Google’s About page.
You can find all the details regarding Histograms here.
History shows the browsing history and option to clear browsing data.
Here, you can see all storage instance of Chrome’s DB.
This option allows you inspect different elements like extensions and pages.
It shows invalidations debug information.
Local state page lists all features and related information.
While playing media, it shows media information.
It shows information about Chrome’s NaCl plugin.
If you wish to see detailed network related information like SPDY, HSTS, HTTP/2, DNS, you need to visit this page.
It shows the network error message.
It open a new tab.
It shows Omnibar (search box) input results like search, shortcuts, and history.
This page stores all the password manager logs.
Google Chrome’s all installed plugins and related options are listed here.
All the currently active policies are listed on this page.
Based on your previous activities, a list of auto-complete and resource predictions are shown on this page.
It’s Chrome’s print preview tab.
It shows the profile tracking data.
It shows you the data about available disk space for Chrome profile directory, and quota details.
It lists all Service Workers register by your web browser. You are also given an option to unregister.
It’s Google Chrome’s main settings page.
This page shows you Chrome’s account activity details, including last sign-in, access tokens etc.
It hosts all suggestions shown at New Tab page.
Shows you supervised user information.
If sync is enabled, this page lists all the details about it.
It shows you information about your computer’s operating system, Chrome version etc.
It shows you Google Chrome usage terms and conditions.
Based on your browsing history, this pages hosts all top websites’ URLs, with and without their thumbnails.
If browsing history is enabled, it records your browsing history.
It shows you the translation preferences.
Useful for debugging, it shows all the current user actions.
It displays detailed information about your Google Chrome web browser.
It shows you all the websites that you’ve browsed in the past.
It creates a dump by downloading stats data and PeerConnection updates.
The recently captured WebRTC logs are listed here.
